{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488385"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:39:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:39:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.22,0.42,0.21,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-10-14T07:16:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T20:53:03+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2021-06-23T03:24:05+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 17:09:06"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"426"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16119"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"9143"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13681"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35208"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a large perianal abscess. This is the sixth such abscess that he has developed in the last ten years. He is otherwise in good health and has no gastrointestinal tract symptoms. He is not on any medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the abscess?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diverticular disease","Crohn\u0027s disease","Anal crypt infection","Hidradenitis suppurativa","Diabetes mellitus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPerianal abscesses are the most common type of anorectal abscess. Located at the anal verge, they can present significant discomfort for patients and may be associated with fever, chills, constipation or diarrhoea. If left untreated they can become complicated due to extension into the ischioanal or intersphincteric space and may in some cases lead to systemic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E90% of all anorectal abscesses develop as a result of non-specific \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstruction of the glandular crypt, followed by the complication of local sepsis\u003C/strong\u003E. Other causes such as Crohn\u0027s disease and hidradenitis suppurativa are much less common, however should be considered in patients with recurrent, or complex disease. Risk factors for a perianal abscess include factors that induce immunosuppression or impact on wound healing such as smoking, HIV, immunosuppressant medications and diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis is based on clinical history and examination, which may yield a fluctuant mass on digital rectal exam. Imaging may be performed in cases that cannot be diagnosed clinically, in which case MRI is the preferred modality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement involves incision and drainage of the abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because, as stated \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehidradenitis suppurativa\u003C/strong\u003E are much less common than local infection; while \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetes\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor for perianal abscess, it is not a cause; and \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticular disease\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the formation of diverticula within the colon which may result in an abscess, but not anorectal or perianal abscesses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common cause of an anorectal abscess is anal crypt obstruction leading to local infection","Perianal abscess is the most common type of anorectal abscess"],"references":["Sigmon DF, Emmanuel B, Tuma F. Perianal Abscess.  StatPearls. Treasure Island (FL)2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459167/","Bender, F., Eckerth, L., Fritzenwanker, M. et al. Drug resistant bacteria in perianal abscesses are frequent and relevant. Sci Rep. 2022. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-022-19123-6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T20:52:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T20:53:24+09:30","number":5,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-08-04T20:52:54+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-426-5.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T180947Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=0e00fe002839e974e0f7a34f7e38049c75ed8b6e4525171023705f36e6e4be7f"},"relationships